  "prompt": "How do junk yards make money?",
  "response": "Junk yards make money through several key revenue streams:\n\n1. **Selling Usable Parts:** Junk yards often dismantle vehicles and sell usable parts. Many people and repair shops look for affordable, second-hand parts which can be significantly cheaper than buying new ones.\n\n2. **Selling Scrap Metal:** Vehicles contain substantial metal content, which can be sold to recycling facilities. The junk yard will strip and clean the metal before selling it as scrap.\n\n3. **Charging Fees:** Junk yards may charge fees for dropping off unwanted vehicles or other large items. They may also charge for entry to the yard where people can search for parts themselves.\n\n4. **Refurbishing and Reselling Vehicles:** Sometimes junk yards find vehicles that can be repaired and resold at a higher value, beyond their parts or scrap value.\n\n5. **Online Sales:** Many junk yards also sell parts online, broadening their customer base and simplifying transactions.\n\n6. **Selling Non-Metal Components:** In addition to metal, junk yards can sell other recyclable materials from vehicles, like plastics and rubber, although these usually fetch lower prices.\n\n7. **Providing Specialized Services:** Some junk yards may offer additional services such as towing, vehicle storage, and dismantling services for a fee. \n\nBy combining these various revenue streams, junk yards can operate profitably.",
